{
  "doc_id": "37433",
  "text": "The gastric environment can negatively affect the stability of NLC after their oral administration. In fact, the acid pH may destabilize lipid carriers, leading to aggregation phenomena, as a consequence of attractive forces, such as Van der Waals and hydrophobic interactions [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] and formation of microparticles, thus negatively influencing the drug release and absorption properties of NLC [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] ). The gastric stability of NLC dispersions was studied in pH 4.5 buffer solution, selected as an average value for infant population, their gastric pH being less acid than that of adults, remaining in the 4-5 range after 2 h of feeding [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] .",
